<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>
 
<example newNamespace>
<p><em>Find the point of intersection of the lines</em></p>
  <md>
    <mrow>9x + 4y &= 19</mrow>
    <mrow>2x - 2y &= 10</mrow>
  </md>

  
<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
<ul>
<li><p>We will use the method of elimination in this case, since multiplying the second equation throughout by <m>2</m> will allow us to eliminate the variable <m>y</m> when the two equations are added together.</p>
  <md>
    <mrow>9x + 4y &= 19</mrow>
    <mrow>2(2x - 2y &= 10)</mrow>
  </md>
</li>
  
<li>
  <p>Carrying out this multiplication, and adding the two equations gives</p>
  <md>
    <mrow>9x + 4y &= 19</mrow>
    <mrow>4x - 4y &= 20</mrow>
    <mrow> \hline 13x &= 39</mrow>
  </md>
</li>
<li><p>Solving the previous equation gives <m>x = 3</m>, which can then be substituted into either of the original equations to solve for <m>y</m>.
  <md>
    <mrow>9(3) + 4y &= 19</mrow>
    <mrow>4y &= 19 - 27</mrow>
    <mrow>y &= -2</mrow>
  </md></p>
</li>
<li><p>We now know that the intersection point is given by <m>(x,y) = (3, -2)</m> but we will also graph our system to check:</p>

<section boxed><title>Graph of the System of Equations</title>
<sideBySide margins="2%" widths="60% 40%">
<graph name="g1" fixed>
  <point name="ip" coords="(3, -2)" fixed styleNumber="5">
    <label>$ip.coords</label>
  </point>
  <line name="line1" equation="9x + 4y = 19" fixed/>
  <line name="line2" equation="2x - 2y = 10" fixed styleNumber="2"/>
</graph>
<section><title>Text Description of Graph:</title> 
  <p>A cartesian axis is shown with the x-axis ranging from negative 8 to positive 8, and the y-axis ranging from negative 8 to positive 8. On the graph, there is a red line with a positive slope corresponding to the first given equation, <m>9x + 4y = 19</m> and a blue line with a negative slope corresponding to the second given equation <m>2x - 2y = 10</m>. A black point is located at the intersection of the two lines, at the coordinates <m>(3,-2)</m></p>
</section>
</sideBySide>
</section>  
</li>
</ul>
  
</example>


</hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<p><m>($x, $y)</m></p>
</solution>


